segments.text: lived the majority of my life and in fact we've lived in the home I guess now about 20 years that across the street from us or it was across the road then from us was just flat land and then there was a creek and then there was pasture land all around and we go back and look now and schools have gone up there are houses everywhere and it's strictly a residential area rather than a
being on the country as it was earlier.
So Bryan has kind of come of age in your, since you've been alive more or less.

Yeah, because I think it was from what I hear my mother tell and my grandmother tell, it was really fairly stagnant for quite a number of years and then just in my lifetime has it really grown and become a city as such rather than just some bunking town.
Okay, we've talked about your father's side of
of the family at the first of this interview.
What can you tell me about your mother's side, the Fosters?
Well, my mother is a combination of Hopkins and Foster, my grandmother being a Hopkins.
She's of Scotch-Irish descent.
We still do have some distant relatives in Scotland and Ireland.
My grandfather came here, my great-grandfather, I know, homesteaded on one side of the road in Steep Hollow.
And his son, which is my grandfather, homesteaded across the road from him, where he still lives today.
And we owned, or rather my relatives owned the majority of the community there and have sold off portions of land.
through the years.
My grandmother was from a small town called Cross that is just a short drive from here.
There's nothing standing there except a few homes and a decrepit general store that is falling apart.
Blink twice and you miss it.
Right.
I think I've been through there.
You were talking about your brothers or your...
Your father's brothers, whatever, selling off the patterns of land.
This is on my mother's side, right.
On your mother's side, right.
Okay.
Can you make a broad statement about the patterns of settlement in early Bryan College Station history?
I think a lot of it had to do with you could raise cattle here.
There was some cattle industry here.
There was even more so the industry of cattle.
call it industry as such, but the raising of cotton, the cotton mills that were here, this brought in a lot of black people used in the cotton, the picking of the cotton and everything.
Not solely black, my mother picked cotton as a child also.
Also, the railroad had quite a hand in bringing people to this area.
In fact, the
Some of the train tracks in Bryan have just recently been lifted.
Right behind my dad's downtown store was where the old passenger train came through town.
There was a depot there.
And part of the land has since been bought up by my dad there in expansion of his facilities and then of the city there by the city hall in Bryan.
What about the river, its effects, the Brazos River?
Yes, the river provided excellent farmland, especially for the cotton growers.
In fact, still today you can go down in what we call the bottom, and find just acres and acres of cotton growing.
You mentioned something about the blacks picking cotton.
We talked about this also earlier with the school integration.
Has there been very much discrimination toward blacks?
How would you describe their situation in the scheme of Bryan College Station history?
Okay, just looking at my family, I can look at three generations right away and tell you I think the cotton industry did have a great deal to do with the black settling in this area.
Once again, we are in the South, so therefore it has been in the past a more or less prejudiced area against the black-white relationship.

Like my grandparents today, through no fault of their own, but merely through the socialization process that they went through as children and as young adults and on through their lives, still refer to the blacks as neighbors.
really don't care to have blacks associate with them except in the capacity of hired hands.
Then you step up to my parents who are not quite so strong in their feeling.
They're not necessarily niggers, but they're colored people.
It's a change in terminology there.
They do accept somewhat the black people as
human beings, I guess you could put it, even though they have been all the way through the ages.
Rather than property.
Right.

But still, we have been brought up, my brothers and I have been brought up very definitely that there is to be a race separation insofar as socializing with, you know, like dating a black or something like that.
And then you come to my generation where I have...
been with and worked with black students.
Not so much in public school because I never went to an integrated school.
And then here at A&M I guess the black population has never been one that has been very high.
But still it's a more liberal attitude that I possess and our brothers possess.
They being younger than me have gone to school with blacks.
I think in comparing my grandparents to myself, a lot of the prejudice has been lost, but yet some still remains, especially in the community.
You have to take every person as an individual.
Let's see.
You were born in this area.
What hospital were you born in?
St. Joseph, but not the one that you see today.
I was going to say, I was wondering.
The St. Joseph that I was born in was over on 28th Street.
It's now the Brazos Valley Mental Rehabilitation Unit.
Somehow appropriate.
Yes, I guess the building got the word that I was born there, so they had to change it over to be appropriate.
There were hospital facilities there.
It was the Catholic Hospital on 28th Street with St. Joseph.
And then there was the Bryan Hospital, which was more or less in downtown Bryan.
It still stands today, but I don't know what facilities are in it now.
Just recently, in the last few years, has Bryan realized, I guess with the growth of the city, they've realized the need for more or less a medical complex.
And there's been an area that has been developed off Villa Maria and 29th Street.
The present.
Yes, there's the present.
St. Joe and Bryan Hospital and just a whole medical complex out there.
What about, oh, you mentioned that some of your descendants were, your predecessors rather, were involved in law enforcement.
Can you mention anything in particular about law enforcement?
In the Bryan College Station area, I mean, we had the famous, renowned campus police and the,
the always efficient college station police, have they always been, have they always had the reputation they have now?
I'll put it that way.
You know, it's amazing.
It's so funny for me to reflect back, because, yeah, we had the same feelings about them, as far as I can remember.
And it's amazing to me now, people always say, you know, how weird the people were.
And it seems like to me, the...
kids that I went to school with that were the biggest tail raisers are now on both the Bryan College Station and campus police force carrying real guns and real bullets.
But in talking to them recently they seem to have matured some and maybe they are doing their job pretty good.
It's funny that you mention that.
Just the other night, just for my own personal interest, I rode with the campus cops.
I don't know if students know this, but you can ride with them at any time just to see what the KKs do.
And I was very fortunate to ride with one of the sergeants who's been here for about 30 years, and I was asking him how has law enforcement changed on the campus here.
And believe it or not, since we've gone co-educational, we've become a much milder campus and have had less carryings on, as you would say, or less, you know, really bad stuff go on.
I was asking about the trends that have changed.
And just in his time, he can remember, like now, CBs are the things that are really getting ripped off.
And when he first came here, it was hubcaps.
Hubcaps.
Another...

thing I think that's worth noting is Chief Luther, who is chief of the KK's now, was with the Texas Rangers for about 20 years and then he was with the Texas Highway Department after that and he has really made a lifelong career out of law enforcement in the state of Texas and I think he's a very admirable man.
Okay, let's get back to the community.
What about

folklore in the local area you know any kind of old ghost stories or anything like that circulating about this area you brought that up when I did my student teaching in Bryan High School I had my students bring in stories that they believed or legends as such that they've heard in this area and it was quite amazing the various stories that the kids brought in
One story that I had a 10th grade student that would vow this was so true.
You can go to Boonville Cemetery, which is a very old cemetery out on Boonville Road off of Villa Maria, at the end of Villa Maria.
It's in North Glion, northeast Glion.
And you can go and part between two certain trees and honk your horn three times.
and you're supposed to be able to see green, glassy, fiery eyes staring into your windshield if you look close enough.
And she swears about this.
Yeah, somehow she was out there on a Friday or Saturday night, and she and the young man she was with happened to honk the horn three times and saw the eyes out there.
Then, let's see, there was closer in College Station here off...
right outside the campus, back in the Northgate area, there was the old haunted dorm, which has been gradually...
I live in one of those.
Which has gradually been detained through the years.
Excuse me.
Then there is also the story there's supposed to be a home here in College Station where after World War II, when there was a huge...
put of students into A&M, veterans coming back to school, a lot of people in the community were called upon to open up their homes to help house students.
And one particular family opened up their attic.
Although it wasn't a very large space, they opened up their attic to allow students to
lived there, and a couple of young men were supposedly to have lived there.

And if you're familiar with the tradition of pulling an all-nighter before exams, one of these students was supposed to have walked the floor, pacing back and forth, studying for his various tests and exams.
And the student was killed before he graduated from A&M.
And it is still said today that at various times, especially during the season where final exams would be
being held.
You can hear this Aggie walking the floor in this particular home and in fact several families have complained of this and moved out of the house and I've talked with them and they do swear.
I've never heard it.
I've never had an occasion to be in the house overnight during that particular time of the year.
Huh.
That's really strange.
Do you know where this house is exactly?
I've been there, but I can't tell you exactly where it is now.
I was taken there, and so I don't remember how to get there.
You mentioned that people threw open their homes to A&M students.
Do you find that this community seems to pull together in crisis situations such as that?
People seem to be pretty friendly.
I think it's a basically friendly community and one that will help other people out.
However, it has grown very much less so in the recent years back when it was a smaller town and everybody knew everybody.
I can remember that.
In fact, today a great majority of the people I still know, but we have had
So many new people move in whether they've been connected with industry or with the university.
So that now, like even I heard just yesterday on the radio, one of the disc jockeys was driving down the street and happened to see a woman who had fallen.
And she hadn't moved in quite a while.
And there seemed to be no effort of her to stand up.
And she had fallen along Texas Avenue and twisted her ankle.
And no one had stopped to help her.
I think it was 670, maybe another street.
So I think right there, that's a sign that maybe people don't stop and take the time to be as friendly as they should be.
However, in traveling all over the states, I do prefer the South as a whole to having friendly or more congenial people.
I wish the campus would go back to its traditional howdy.
Yes.
Because that helped...
spread congeniality.
I think that's only recently died, too.
I'd say this year.
I mean, it has been dying, I'll admit, but I know at least half of the student body, you know, including the core, used to do the old Howdy tradition.
I know all the people on the streets in Bryan are pretty much that way, too, but this year it just seems like...
You know, just wow, nothing.
Well, especially being our centennial year, I hate to think that one of our more famous traditions has died.

And I hope that people will, I know I hear complaints that somebody's, you know, really in a crummy mood and they walk to class and they hear this stereo howdy, howdy, howdy, howdy, howdy every time they turn around.
But yet, I really don't think people mean it as just a tape recording of saying howdy every time they turn around.
meet somebody, just a pleasant smile, even if they don't speak.
But I would like to see that one tradition revived.
And I don't think it's dead completely.
I think it's dying, but I'd like to see it revived.
Let's talk about the community again.
What is the social life like in Bryan?
What do people in Bryan do for a good time?
What have they done historically, back from the good old days with the Sunday go-to-meet-and-dinner-on-the-grounds type thing?
How has that evolved?
We had a lot of that.
It was a very strong, I think it had a very strong religious founding.
And there has been a lot of social life that has generated around the church and the youth activities from that.
However, in recent years, people have grown out of that to a certain extent.
which I hesitate to say whether that's been good or bad.
I know when I was growing up, I felt like the only place to go was either to the show or to the show or to the show.
How about places like Pooh's Park?
Did that appeal to you?
Was that around then?
Did they have anything like that?
Now we had the miniature golf course in the parks.
That was about it as far as extracurricular activities for a child growing up.
I think now the community is seeing a need for having facilities for children as such.
In fact, you might directly tie that into the drug scare that we had.

recent years where all of the quote-unquote establishment felt like the younger generation was going to the dogs and maybe they realized that there wasn't enough to do in some areas for their children.
And that's why a lot of people have gone to seeking out and providing recreation for the various age groups.
Yes, I want to get on a little bit of the religion.
You said that it was basically a pretty religious area early.
What kind of religions
were available to people here in College Station?
Once again, I'm more familiar with the Bryan area rather than College Station.
Oh, well, fine.
There is, of course, always been your Southern Baptists who have been a very strong group in the South as a whole.
Your Methodist is another very strong church.
And then I suppose to the Spanish and Italian descent, we've also had a very strong Catholic influence on our area.
Then, of course, you have your other religions.
I hate to be leaving out religion, but I think those are really the main three that have been the largest and the most functional in this area.
Can you think of anything else, unusual stories?
Anything you might add?
No.
I really can't.
The community has really changed.
As I remember, and I know in our mothers' and grandparents' memories, it has really changed.
For the better?
I don't know.
There's a certain neatness about a small town.
but yet there seems to be more social life, especially for a young person in a larger town.
I think this is still a nice-sized town to raise a family in, but it needs to have a lot more to offer, especially with this being such a college-oriented community.
I know the one thing that has really...
I know we're not supposed to really get on the college, but
One thing that has really changed is, like, A&M itself and the fact that, like, everyone used to be all core.

And I can remember walking down the street, you know, Saturday afternoon or whatever, and you could see a guy just, you know, dressed in civilian clothes with his head just as bald as a billiard ball and just a spit shine on it.
And you knew immediately he was a freshman in the corps.
He didn't have to be in uniform to tell that.
And it's now they all have hair and now they're not all necessarily in uniform on campus.
And then with the women going into the Corps it still startles me to see women.
And now that we've got two juniors I'm anticipating to see what they'll look like in boots next year.
and see exactly what kind of, you know, will they wear the gaucho pants with boots, or are they going to wear the boot pants with boots, or exactly what they will look like.
I'm glad we've stopped shaving heads.
I don't think the girls would really go in for that.
If the school were to, say, were to mystically go bankrupt tomorrow,
If they had to shut A&M down, Federal Education Act or something, shut A&M down.
State.
State.
Okay, do you think that the Bryan College Station would survive?
At the same age I am now, if you'd asked me that 10 or 15 years ago, I would say that the whole town would probably just be wiped out.
or it would just be a town like Hearn or Navasota, you know, just a small community.
The university gives so much to the area.
However, I think we've got enough now, speaking industry-wise and business-wise, that they would survive as a town and probably a nice-sized town.
However, of course, your, like, weaker eating establishments and things like this may find themselves looking for more customers and close down.
In fact, very much so.
But I think it would survive to a certain extent.
It wouldn't be near the area that it is now, but there would be something.
Well, and because people have their roots here, too.
For one reason, we stayed around here.
I don't know what that reason is right now.
For some unknown reason, my dad decided to come here.
He's made it very good here.
He's decided to stay and has had no desire to leave.
I have a feeling there are many other people, even if the university was to dissipate somehow during the night, that they would too choose to stay here.
Well, that's all I have.
Do you want to add anything?
No, I can't think of anything.
I really enjoyed it.
Thank you for your time.
